I needed to restart once or twice to get the Crowd Server completely started. (For one occurrence of the issue, I only needed to restart once; for another time, I needed to restart twice.)

Resources protected with AuthzSVNCrowdAccessFile are occasionally reporting spurious authentication failure.
The same credentials are being supplied each time, and the Crowd server doesn't show any evidence of failed authentication attempts.
Apache's logs show the cwdapache modules logging as:
{code}
[Xxx Xxx yy yy:yy:yy yyyy] [error] [client xx.xx.xx.xx] Access denied: 'xxxxxxxxxx' GET xxxx:/yyyy
{code}
And Apache's logging of the final decision as:
{code}
[Xxx Xxx yy yy:yy:yy yyyy] [error] [client xx.xx.xx.xx] user xxxx: 
authentication failure for "/xxxx/xxxx": Password Mismatch
{code}

Crowd Query Language supports escaping of characters, so:

{noformat}
name = "a\"b"
{noformat}

is a valid way to check that the name is exactly {{a"b}}. However, it currently passes through the expression, rather than the evaluated form, with backslashes included as literally specified.
